Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Co-Operative Bank, Nigeria Breweries, Fan Milk

-- B y   S a r a h   M c G r e g o r   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 
2011-04-27T16:27:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-27/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-co-operative-bank-nigeria-breweries-fan-milk.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index rallied 1.5 percent to 25,399.89 by the 2:30 p.m.
close in Lagos, the commercial capital, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index strengthened for a
third day, gaining 0.1 percent to 1,090.76 by the 3 p.m. close
in Accra. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose for a second day,
strengthening less than 0.1 percent to 2,058.69 at the 1.30 p.m.
close in  Port Louis .  Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell less than 0.1 percent to 75.01
by 3 p.m. in Nairobi.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Co-operative Bank of Kenya Ltd. (COOP)  , the country’s
fourth-biggest bank by assets, rose the most in eight months
after first-quarter profit jumped 58 percent. The lender surged
95 cents, or 5.5 percent, to 18.35 shillings, the biggest
intraday jump since August 2010.  Net income advanced to 1.64 billion shillings ($19.6
million) in the three months to March 31, from 1.04 billion
shillings in the same period a year earlier. Net interest
income, the difference between what a bank pays out for deposits
and charges for loans, climbed 46 percent to 2.85 billion
shillings, Co-operative Bank said.  Fan Milk Ltd. (FML)  , a Ghanaian manufacturer of food and
dairy products, climbed to a four-month high as it announced
first-quarter profit grew 2 percent. Revenue grew 4 percent in
the period.  The shares rose 3 pesewas, or 1.1 percent, to 2.56 cedis,
the highest since Dec. 20, according to Bloomberg data.  Nigerian Breweries Plc (NB)  , the country’s biggest
brewer by market value, gained the most in more than a week
after it said shareholders will vote on its planned acquisition
of two other brewers.  The stock gained 72 kobo, or 0.8 percent, to 86.50 naira,
the highest since April 18.  To contact the reporters on this story:
